00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:03.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:23.420 --> 00:00:25.530
&gt;&gt;JOHN FENN: I'm John Fenn from
the American Folklife Center

00:00:25.530 --> 00:00:29.240
at the Library of Congress and I'm
here today with Ledward Kaapana,

00:00:29.240 --> 00:00:31.970
slack key guitar player,
ukulele player and singer.

00:00:31.970 --> 00:00:36.210
And we're going to chat a little
bit about Hawaiian music, culture,

00:00:36.210 --> 00:00:38.920
language and get your background.

00:00:38.920 --> 00:00:40.760
&gt;&gt;LEDWARD KAAPANA:
We're going to have fun.

00:00:40.760 --> 00:00:42.680
&gt;&gt;JOHN FENN: we're
going to have fun.

00:00:42.680 --> 00:00:47.460
So, I know you talk a lot
about family and learning how

00:00:47.460 --> 00:00:48.760
to play as a young child.

00:00:48.760 --> 00:00:51.280
Why don't you give us a
brief overview of growing

00:00:51.280 --> 00:00:54.680
up with all this music around you
and how you picked up the guitar.

00:00:54.680 --> 00:00:57.760
&gt;&gt;LEDWARD KAAPANA: Well, Because
living in Kalapana we were

00:00:57.760 --> 00:00:59.650
so isolated from everything else.

00:00:59.650 --> 00:01:05.020
No electricity, you know, learn
how to live the old style,

00:01:05.020 --> 00:01:09.370
we went fishing, we went
hunting, you know, swimming.

00:01:09.370 --> 00:01:12.970
And besides all that there's music.

00:01:12.970 --> 00:01:18.370
My dad, my mom, uncles and
aunties, they all played music, so,

00:01:18.370 --> 00:01:23.900 position:56%
I was so fortune, growing up every
day, every day I hear music and back

00:01:23.900 --> 00:01:28.340
in those days my family
no one plays music.

00:01:28.340 --> 00:01:32.980
They played from the heart,
you know, from within.

00:01:32.980 --> 00:01:36.730
So, that's way I learned
how to play this music.

00:01:36.730 --> 00:01:41.690
Down the keys, you know, it would
be the major keys like G, F, A,

00:01:41.690 --> 00:01:46.920
anything after that would have been
second F, Second A. Which I found

00:01:46.920 --> 00:01:52.390
out A7 is second A,
C7 is second F, so,

00:01:52.390 --> 00:01:57.710
then I had all my uncles
they all played music.

00:01:57.710 --> 00:02:00.150
Uncles and aunties they
all play slack keys.

00:02:00.150 --> 00:02:01.450
&gt;&gt; Okay.

00:02:01.450 --> 00:02:03.750
&gt;&gt; so, as I was growing up I
could see all the different style.

00:02:03.750 --> 00:02:08.910
So, I learned by watching how
they fingered the keyboard

00:02:08.910 --> 00:02:10.210
and how they tuned.

00:02:10.210 --> 00:02:14.350
I remember all the tunings
as I was growing up.

00:02:14.350 --> 00:02:17.370
&gt;&gt; Which tuning do you
use most often now?

00:02:17.370 --> 00:02:20.810 position:56%
&gt;&gt;LEDWARD KAAPANA: we call this the
tera fast [assumed spelling] tuning.

00:02:20.810 --> 00:02:26.050
What it is the standard
tuning on the guitar,

00:02:26.050 --> 00:02:30.410
the first string right here, so
this would be an E. so, what I did,

00:02:30.410 --> 00:02:34.030
I dropped that E down
to a D, so it's a D now.

00:02:34.030 --> 00:02:35.330
the sound of the E would be here.

00:02:35.330 --> 00:02:42.320
So, I went down to D. And this
stays the same, this is a B string.

00:02:42.320 --> 00:02:44.490
Stays the same right
here, this is a G string.

00:02:44.490 --> 00:02:49.860
And then right here the
fourth string it's D

00:02:49.860 --> 00:02:58.600
and then the fifth string from
the A. I tuned it down to G.

00:02:58.600 --> 00:03:02.910
And then the sixth string is like
the first string, from an E I went

00:03:02.910 --> 00:03:06.430
down to a D. So, there's two
D's and we treat these --

00:03:06.430 --> 00:03:13.490
one here, one there, this is octave
and the other one is right here.

00:03:13.490 --> 00:03:19.670
So. This all the D notes.

00:03:19.670 --> 00:03:20.970
And then you have the B's.

00:03:20.970 --> 00:03:25.590
Then I have two G's, the third
string and the fifth string.

00:03:25.590 --> 00:03:30.100
And when you strum
against the strings

00:03:30.100 --> 00:03:32.820
like this it's a G major chord,
on a standard [inaudible],

00:03:32.820 --> 00:03:40.080
the standard when you have
to hold the G like this.

00:03:40.080 --> 00:03:45.540
now I don't have to, I just go...

00:03:45.540 --> 00:03:48.120
And that's what's lucky,
we tuned the guitar,

00:03:48.120 --> 00:03:49.870
so we call this a tera fast tuning.

00:03:49.870 --> 00:03:56.520
And the technique of playing
this style the thumb does all the

00:03:56.520 --> 00:03:58.320
base notes.

00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:04.040
[ Guitar Strumming ]

00:04:04.040 --> 00:04:06.170
So the thumb is doing.

00:04:06.170 --> 00:04:11.510
and then the finger does
all the melody chords.

00:04:11.510 --> 00:04:22.040
[ Guitar Strumming ]

00:04:22.040 --> 00:04:25.120
So, you have the base going steady

00:04:25.120 --> 00:04:28.880
and then the finger's doing
all of the melody chords.

00:04:28.880 --> 00:04:31.090
&gt;&gt;JOHN FENN: You make
it sound so easy.

00:04:31.090 --> 00:04:32.390
&gt;&gt;LEDWARD KAAPANA: it is.

00:04:32.390 --> 00:04:34.390
&gt;&gt;JOHN FENN: So, when you were
younger and there was music all

00:04:34.390 --> 00:04:38.530 position:56%
around you, did someone put a guitar
into your hand and say, "Here,

00:04:38.530 --> 00:04:42.600
play," or did you pick one up out
of your own out of inspiration?

00:04:42.600 --> 00:04:46.020
&gt;&gt;LEDWARD KAAPANA: When I was young
we couldn't touch the guitars.

00:04:46.020 --> 00:04:51.260
All we could do was watch
them play, you know.

00:04:51.260 --> 00:04:54.770
you know, living in Kalapana we're
so isolated from everything else.

00:04:54.770 --> 00:04:57.080
So, we used to have
parties that goes

00:04:57.080 --> 00:04:59.960
on for months, not weeks, months.

00:04:59.960 --> 00:05:02.660
and from the first
house to the last house

00:05:02.660 --> 00:05:04.260
in Kalapana we were all related.

00:05:04.260 --> 00:05:07.960
So, everybody we would share
whatever we could bring.

00:05:07.960 --> 00:05:11.260
You know, we're fishing, some were
hunting, and we all shared the food

00:05:11.260 --> 00:05:13.660
and the parties keep on going.

00:05:13.660 --> 00:05:19.210 position:56%
So, the only time we could touch the
guitar is when they were all drink.

00:05:19.210 --> 00:05:21.100
You know, they having fun.

00:05:21.100 --> 00:05:23.170
After that we don't
touch it when they --

00:05:23.170 --> 00:05:24.980
you know, because they don't
want you to touch the guitars,

00:05:24.980 --> 00:05:28.890
because they don't want the
guitar brake or, you know,

00:05:28.890 --> 00:05:33.640 position:56%
so we don't touch it, so I just sit
there and observe what is happening,

00:05:33.640 --> 00:05:37.810
how they tune the guitar
and I'm just listening.

00:05:37.810 --> 00:05:40.650
And the trick is the
ear have to be good

00:05:40.650 --> 00:05:42.310
to know what you're doing, yeah.

00:05:42.310 --> 00:05:43.720
Have to really listen.

00:05:43.720 --> 00:05:46.600
&gt;&gt;JOHN FENN: So, you start
playing when you were 4?

00:05:46.600 --> 00:05:49.140
&gt;&gt;LEDWARD KAAPANA: When I was
6 years old I played ukulele.

00:05:49.140 --> 00:05:50.440
I started with the ukulele.

00:05:50.440 --> 00:05:51.740
&gt;&gt;JOHN FENN: Okay.

00:05:51.740 --> 00:05:53.490
&gt;&gt;LEDWARD KAAPANA: Yeah,
started with the ukulele and then

00:05:53.490 --> 00:05:57.020
as the years went on I
started playing this.

00:05:57.020 --> 00:05:58.320
we were getting older already.

00:05:58.320 --> 00:06:01.670
When I was about 8 years old
I could touch the guitar.

00:06:01.670 --> 00:06:02.970
&gt;&gt;JOHN FENN: Okay.

00:06:02.970 --> 00:06:05.240
&gt;&gt;LEDWARD KAAPANA: And I
start playing like, you know,

00:06:05.240 --> 00:06:07.280
strumming all the rhythm.

00:06:07.280 --> 00:06:10.140
My dad and them playing the music.

00:06:10.140 --> 00:06:12.850
And then my mom says, "Oh, you
got good rhythm, you know,"

00:06:12.850 --> 00:06:15.380
because we listening
it and we playing it.

00:06:15.380 --> 00:06:20.820
And finally we were able to play
with them at parties or whatever.

00:06:20.820 --> 00:06:22.120
&gt;&gt;JOHN FENN: Okay.

00:06:22.120 --> 00:06:27.090
And in that situation would you
learn by playing or would an uncle

00:06:27.090 --> 00:06:29.060
or your dad sit down
with you and teach you.

00:06:29.060 --> 00:06:30.360
&gt;&gt;LEDWARD KAAPANA: Oh, no.

00:06:30.360 --> 00:06:32.580
they didn't teach us.

00:06:32.580 --> 00:06:37.110
I learned by watching what they
did and remember what they did

00:06:37.110 --> 00:06:40.470
and that's how I learned, you know.

00:06:40.470 --> 00:06:44.950
Same like them, you know, just knew
the music keys and the tune in,

00:06:44.950 --> 00:06:49.710
I remember all the tune ins.

00:06:49.710 --> 00:06:53.860
But my uncle used to be kind
of one step ahead of us,

00:06:53.860 --> 00:06:56.720
because he knew I wanted to
learn how to play the guitar.

00:06:56.720 --> 00:06:59.740
So, what he would do, because he
know every time he put the guitar

00:06:59.740 --> 00:07:04.180
down I grab the guitar
and forget the fingerings.

00:07:04.180 --> 00:07:07.660
Not knowing that every time he put
the guitar down he always slacken

00:07:07.660 --> 00:07:11.930
on the other string that I
would see it, he puts it there.

00:07:11.930 --> 00:07:13.230
&gt;&gt;JOHN FENN: Keeping
you on your toes.

00:07:13.230 --> 00:07:14.530
&gt;&gt;LEDWARD KAAPANA:
keeping me on my toes.

00:07:14.530 --> 00:07:16.920
Until I finally found
out what he was doing.

00:07:16.920 --> 00:07:20.190
So, I guess, he puts it down there,
he walks outside of the house

00:07:20.190 --> 00:07:22.670
and he's outside listening
and he's having fun.

00:07:22.670 --> 00:07:26.100 position:56%
Because in Kalapan we don't have
electricity, so we don't have no TV.

00:07:26.100 --> 00:07:29.510
I was like the cartoon actor
for him and he's laughing.

00:07:29.510 --> 00:07:34.010
So, finally I caught on because
the thing that he sound --

00:07:34.010 --> 00:07:35.460
I see his finger like this.

00:07:35.460 --> 00:07:39.190
sounds good, yeah?

00:07:39.190 --> 00:07:44.830
So, the next thing I know, he slack
this string so it wouldn't sound

00:07:44.830 --> 00:07:47.820 position:56%
like this, it would sound like this.

00:07:47.820 --> 00:07:49.120
I said, something wrong
with this string.

00:07:49.120 --> 00:07:54.000
And then I found out, I
tune it up, you know, soft.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:59.630
And I said, ah, there's the
note, because my ears are good.

00:07:59.630 --> 00:08:02.770
I knew what he was doing.

00:08:02.770 --> 00:08:07.470
I slack another string
on him, put it down.

00:08:07.470 --> 00:08:08.770
he caught on.

00:08:08.770 --> 00:08:12.050
He look at me and he says, "Oh, you
smart, now I'm going to teach you."

00:08:12.050 --> 00:08:17.220 position:56%
And when he say he's going to teach
me, all he does is just plays guitar

00:08:17.220 --> 00:08:19.560
and tells me watch what he's doing.

00:08:19.560 --> 00:08:20.860
yep.

00:08:20.860 --> 00:08:23.260
&gt;&gt;JOHN FENN: And what
about the singing?

00:08:23.260 --> 00:08:25.180
You learned to sing
from your mother?

00:08:25.180 --> 00:08:27.220 position:56%
&gt;&gt;LEDWARD KAAPANA: yes, from my mom.

00:08:27.220 --> 00:08:34.240
Then the little key key, the high
falsetto singing I learned it

00:08:34.240 --> 00:08:39.540
from a gentlemen back in 1963.

00:08:39.540 --> 00:08:44.700
He came -- because, by the 7th
grade we were playing music.

00:08:44.700 --> 00:08:47.420
I mean, me and my brother,
we were just jamming.

00:08:47.420 --> 00:08:50.960
We were playing like professions.

00:08:50.960 --> 00:08:54.110
So, the gentlemen came
in and asked my daddy

00:08:54.110 --> 00:08:56.910
if we could take off
and play with him.

00:08:56.910 --> 00:09:02.530
So, we were only 8, we played in
the night club that served liquor,

00:09:02.530 --> 00:09:07.560
so my dad and mom had to come
there and we had child labor board

00:09:07.560 --> 00:09:10.690
and that gentlemen used to
sing all the time falsetto.

00:09:10.690 --> 00:09:13.350
The last song I did
that's the song he sang.

00:09:13.350 --> 00:09:15.750
And just watching what he did.

00:09:15.750 --> 00:09:17.740
And it just came out natural.

00:09:17.740 --> 00:09:19.820
You know, like watching
how they play music.

00:09:19.820 --> 00:09:22.950
I just listen to him and
it just came natural.

00:09:22.950 --> 00:09:26.870
And after that I see
all the guys singing,

00:09:26.870 --> 00:09:30.110
before they called it falsetto.

00:09:32.440 --> 00:09:35.350
I used to ask him,
I said, "Gentlemen,"

00:09:35.350 --> 00:09:40.120
his name was David Chung, he's
best already, I said, "David,

00:09:40.120 --> 00:09:41.790
how do you sing high like that?"

00:09:41.790 --> 00:09:49.320 position:56%
He said, "Well, when I was a baby,"
yeah, I says, "I used to cry a lot."

00:09:49.320 --> 00:09:51.850
Oh, yeah. I said, "yeah,
I used to scream and cry."

00:09:51.850 --> 00:09:54.140
But he was just joking.

00:09:54.140 --> 00:09:58.160
&gt;&gt;JOHN FENN: It seems like
humor is a big part of -- KL

00:09:58.160 --> 00:10:05.280
&gt;&gt; yeah, that's why I'm like
this, always having fun.

