00:29:42.480 --> 00:29:45.290
&gt;&gt;JOHN FENN: Did you pick
up any techniques from them

00:29:45.290 --> 00:29:47.690
or were you just teaching them?

00:29:47.690 --> 00:29:49.230
&gt;&gt;LEDWARD KAAPANA: No, we sit down

00:29:49.230 --> 00:29:51.470
and Hawaiians we call it conna
kopila [phonetic spelling]

00:29:51.470 --> 00:29:57.760
where we just jam and everybody
just having fun watching different.

00:29:57.760 --> 00:30:00.020
We all have our own style.

00:30:00.020 --> 00:30:03.630
To sit down and play we
just giggle like, oh, wow.

00:30:03.630 --> 00:30:09.580
You know, Ray Flack, I remember
Ray Flack he goes on the stage,

00:30:09.580 --> 00:30:12.880
first time I see him,
the stage is all dark

00:30:12.880 --> 00:30:17.980 position:56%
and all you see is this spotlight on
his back and his back facing the --

00:30:17.980 --> 00:30:19.540
and somebody goes,
"There's Ray Flack."

00:30:19.540 --> 00:30:27.150
And he goes like [blows] and all
this dust, you know, and he goes,

00:30:27.150 --> 00:30:32.020 position:56%
bang, and more dust and then he
starts -- you know, say, "wow, man."

00:30:32.020 --> 00:30:36.570
I just like, oh, man,
I have to follow him.

00:30:36.570 --> 00:30:37.870
I'm the next guy.

00:30:37.870 --> 00:30:39.170
I said, "Oh, man, that's
a hard act."

00:30:39.170 --> 00:30:41.070
and I say -- but you know,

00:30:41.070 --> 00:30:43.510
let me tune this guitar,
I show you what I do.

00:30:43.510 --> 00:30:48.740
[ Guitar Sounds ]

00:30:48.740 --> 00:30:51.610
Because -- see, I had
to follow him, I said,

00:30:51.610 --> 00:30:53.510
"I got to get something
down," you know.

00:30:53.510 --> 00:31:02.040
[ Guitar Sounds ]

00:31:02.040 --> 00:31:04.380
So I did a song called, my
uncle taught me this song,

00:31:04.380 --> 00:31:06.510
it's called monolo --
monolosaki [phonetic spelling].

00:31:06.510 --> 00:31:09.440
[ Music ]

00:31:09.440 --> 00:31:12.290
And he over hands the guitar
like this and he says,

00:31:12.290 --> 00:31:16.940
"The song that will start called
the Hawaiian [inaudible]."

00:31:16.940 --> 00:31:20.510
You know, he said, "all you
have to do is watch the hand,

00:31:20.510 --> 00:31:23.100
and it never leaves the
-- or watch the fingers,

00:31:23.100 --> 00:31:24.430
they never leave the hand."

00:31:24.430 --> 00:31:27.510
So, and the song go like this.

00:31:27.510 --> 00:32:03.220
[ Music ]

00:32:03.220 --> 00:32:05.400
So, I did the song right after him.

00:32:05.400 --> 00:32:06.700
She said I have to go on there.

00:32:06.700 --> 00:32:08.150
I said, "oh, I got to do the song."

00:32:08.150 --> 00:32:14.630
So I did the song and in my pocket
I had this battery fan, you know,

00:32:14.630 --> 00:32:18.340
on the airplane I turn on the
fan it was hot in the place.

00:32:18.340 --> 00:32:20.750
So, I got this fan,
huh, I take the fan off

00:32:20.750 --> 00:32:22.620
and people all clap, yeah, yeah.

00:32:22.620 --> 00:32:26.190
Then after the song's done, I
take the fan out, I go like this.

00:32:26.190 --> 00:32:30.430
You know, my fingers, you know
my fingers, to go like this.

00:32:30.430 --> 00:32:31.730
they started clapping.

00:32:31.730 --> 00:32:35.380
So, I walked in the back in
the back into the dressing room

00:32:35.380 --> 00:32:37.360
and Ray Flack he's back
there and he looks and me

00:32:37.360 --> 00:32:40.670
and goes, "Gee, I like your act."

00:32:40.670 --> 00:32:43.060
I tell him, "I like yours too."

00:32:43.060 --> 00:32:46.150
We had good fun after that,
we started sharing music

00:32:46.150 --> 00:32:50.180
and just having a ball
in the back there.

00:32:50.180 --> 00:32:51.520
&gt;&gt;JOHN FENN: yeah,
that sounds pretty fun.

00:32:51.520 --> 00:32:53.260
&gt;&gt;LEDWARD KAAPANA: Then
again, we had [inaudible].

00:32:53.260 --> 00:32:56.090
I got to know all of them so good.

00:32:56.090 --> 00:33:01.970
I mean, I learned so much from them
about getting real professional

00:33:01.970 --> 00:33:06.710
on the stage and complimenting
one another, it was awesome, yeah.

00:33:06.710 --> 00:33:11.220
&gt;&gt;JOHN FENN: And then
-- so that was a tour.

00:33:11.220 --> 00:33:12.800
&gt;&gt;LEDWARD KAAPANA:
That was a tour, yeah.

00:33:12.800 --> 00:33:16.010
&gt;&gt;JOHN FENN: and you've also
done recordings with others,

00:33:16.010 --> 00:33:19.360
with people from other
styles as well, haven't you?

00:33:19.360 --> 00:33:20.660 position:56%
&gt;&gt;Ledward Kaapana: Yeah, Eric Gibbs.

00:33:20.660 --> 00:33:27.010
Eric Gibbs is one of
them, I played with him.

00:33:27.010 --> 00:33:28.310
Quite a few.

00:33:28.310 --> 00:33:29.610
&gt;&gt;JOHN FENN: So, as you're
exploring all these styles,

00:33:29.610 --> 00:33:35.390
do you feel like you're continuing
to learn and expand your --

00:33:35.390 --> 00:33:36.690
&gt;&gt;LEDWARD KAAPANA: Yeah.

00:33:36.690 --> 00:33:37.990
After [inaudible], you know.

00:33:37.990 --> 00:33:44.570
But one thing -- one thing about
playing with any artist, you know,

00:33:44.570 --> 00:33:52.900
I play with all kinds of music,
I'm not afraid to play with anybody

00:33:52.900 --> 00:33:54.820
because you got to pay attention.

00:33:54.820 --> 00:33:57.350
The ears to me is the
most important.

00:33:57.350 --> 00:34:00.420
So, I listen to what they're doing.

00:34:00.420 --> 00:34:03.590
you know, when we go out
there and do festivals,

00:34:03.590 --> 00:34:05.650
especially when we
staying at the hotel,

00:34:05.650 --> 00:34:08.720
you got all these blue grass
players, country western,

00:34:08.720 --> 00:34:10.440
they all in the lobby playing.

00:34:10.440 --> 00:34:14.220
I walk in the room and so I'll
just pick a band and I say,

00:34:14.220 --> 00:34:15.520
"Hey, can I join you guys?"

00:34:15.520 --> 00:34:17.200
They say, "Yeah, sure, come in."

00:34:17.200 --> 00:34:19.980
So, I jump in with
the blue grass guys.

00:34:19.980 --> 00:34:27.260
They're playing and while they're
playing I hear how the music going

00:34:27.260 --> 00:34:28.600
and I'm ready in the back of them.

00:34:28.600 --> 00:34:30.440
They don't tell me, "Oh,
we're in the key of G

00:34:30.440 --> 00:34:31.740
or we're in the key of A."

00:34:31.740 --> 00:34:34.530
I just hear that, I find it and
I'm already behind them playing it

00:34:34.530 --> 00:34:36.940
and they look at me like, wow.

00:34:36.940 --> 00:34:42.970 position:56%
Because to hear this Hawaiian flavor
mixing up with the blue grass.

00:34:42.970 --> 00:34:44.860
So, they tell me, "You
want to take one?"

00:34:44.860 --> 00:34:47.840
Yes, so I take a lead, they
look at me and they go,

00:34:47.840 --> 00:34:49.250
"Whoa, take another one."

00:34:49.250 --> 00:34:50.690
Sure, I take another one.

00:34:50.690 --> 00:34:53.530
And then it goes around,
right, everybody takes one.

00:34:53.530 --> 00:34:57.480 position:56%
So, they goes to the next guy, says,
"Oh, it's your turn," the guy says,

00:34:57.480 --> 00:35:01.040
"Nuh uh, not after this guy."

00:35:01.040 --> 00:35:03.570
I say, -- you know, we
all have fun and then --

00:35:03.570 --> 00:35:05.030
they tell me, "How you
learn how to play?"

00:35:05.030 --> 00:35:07.740
I said, "Oh, I just listen."

00:35:07.740 --> 00:35:11.970
I said, I don't -- if you know
the music they're playing,

00:35:11.970 --> 00:35:16.350
but I have real good ears, I
just listen and I'm right there

00:35:16.350 --> 00:35:18.970
with them, just having fun.

00:35:18.970 --> 00:35:20.960 position:56%
And got to come from inside, always.

00:35:20.960 --> 00:35:25.630
If you really pay attention
and I always said the ears got

00:35:25.630 --> 00:35:28.340
to be good listening
to what's happening.

00:35:28.340 --> 00:35:32.480
If not, if you don't listen
good, you know, I going to be all

00:35:32.480 --> 00:35:34.560
over the places instead
of paying attention.

00:35:34.560 --> 00:35:38.600
Like back home I always tell them,
when I used to play in a group,

00:35:38.600 --> 00:35:41.520
you know, we always call a
guest artist to come on stage,

00:35:41.520 --> 00:35:44.560
so I always tell them,
somebody come on the stage.

00:35:44.560 --> 00:35:47.540
You got to pay attention, pay
attention to what they're doing.

00:35:47.540 --> 00:35:49.180
Huh? They tell me, "Huh."

00:35:49.180 --> 00:35:53.690
I say, "Yeah, because if
you think you know the song,

00:35:53.690 --> 00:35:56.430
you don't know a song, they're
going to do the same son, you know,

00:35:56.430 --> 00:35:58.510
but everybody got their own style."

00:35:58.510 --> 00:36:01.680
So you got to listen to the
beat, how they sing them,

00:36:01.680 --> 00:36:05.030
because I told them,
you know, the guy came,

00:36:05.030 --> 00:36:08.410 position:56%
he's singing the same song, this guy
I know, he's paying attention, no,

00:36:08.410 --> 00:36:10.300
he knows the song,
so he plays the song.

00:36:10.300 --> 00:36:12.880
Next thing I know, the
guys not even over there,

00:36:12.880 --> 00:36:15.450
and this guy's changing key on him.

00:36:15.450 --> 00:36:16.750
See, you got to pay attention.

00:36:16.750 --> 00:36:19.040
The guy doesn't sing like
you, he sings his way,

00:36:19.040 --> 00:36:21.850
so you got to pay attention
to whoever comes on the stage.

00:36:21.850 --> 00:36:25.090 position:56%
Like, me, if I go on stager to play
for somebody, I got to pay attention

00:36:25.090 --> 00:36:28.960
to what he do so I can be right
behind him complimenting or yeah.

00:36:28.960 --> 00:36:31.690
&gt;&gt;JOHN FENN: So, it
seems like to me, I mean,

00:36:31.690 --> 00:36:35.560
part of the stories you've been
telling about growing up with

00:36:35.560 --> 00:36:40.670
such music around you and the
tradition of slack key is something

00:36:40.670 --> 00:36:46.000
that is flexible, so you're
continuing it be exploring it

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:47.300
and expanding it.

00:36:47.300 --> 00:36:53.680
&gt;&gt;LEDWARD KAAPANA: it actually,
yeah, yeah, and sharing it.

00:36:53.680 --> 00:36:54.980
Yep.

00:36:54.980 --> 00:36:56.280
&gt;&gt;JOHN FENN: Okay.

00:36:56.280 --> 00:36:59.370
&gt;&gt;LEDWARD KAAPANA: And besides
slack key I do a standard tune.

00:36:59.370 --> 00:37:02.490
I love standard tuning, because
the standard tuning you can play

00:37:02.490 --> 00:37:04.330
anything, you know.

00:37:04.330 --> 00:37:05.670
I'm all over the guitar.

00:37:05.670 --> 00:37:08.650
The slack key you're
limited to certain.

00:37:08.650 --> 00:37:13.710
The reason why I play slack
key was because I play solo,

00:37:13.710 --> 00:37:17.950
so I try to make the music full
and I'm singing [inaudible].

00:37:17.950 --> 00:37:20.560
So, that way it sounds
there's somebody

00:37:20.560 --> 00:37:22.350
in the back helping you playing it.

00:37:22.350 --> 00:37:23.650
So you sound full.

00:37:23.650 --> 00:37:26.810
So, that's why I always
play slack key.

00:37:26.810 --> 00:37:30.270
But if I play with a
group I tune it up.

00:37:30.270 --> 00:37:36.710 position:56%
And when I play [inaudible], so when
I turn my guitar up to standard,

00:37:36.710 --> 00:37:40.600
Josh says, "Oh, no,
it's kick ass time."

00:37:40.600 --> 00:37:42.720
He knows, he just knows.

00:37:42.720 --> 00:37:45.660
And when I -- he says,
"Oh, he's going to --

00:37:45.660 --> 00:37:47.920
" There's no limit on the standard.

00:37:47.920 --> 00:37:51.950
To me no limit you do
anything you want to do on it.

00:37:51.950 --> 00:37:53.820
I just -- I mean, you
got everything,

00:37:53.820 --> 00:37:56.210
I can play any kind on this.

00:37:56.210 --> 00:38:01.480
I can do it on the slack key tune,
but the slack key tune you have

00:38:01.480 --> 00:38:04.920
to work harder than
the standard tuning.

00:38:04.920 --> 00:38:09.050
Yeah, the standard tuning, I
love standard tuning, I love.

00:38:09.050 --> 00:38:11.280
&gt;&gt;JOHN FENN: When you were growing
up, with people switching back

00:38:11.280 --> 00:38:13.450
and forth between slack key
tuning and standard tuning,

00:38:13.450 --> 00:38:18.330
with those month long parties
and the musical environment

00:38:18.330 --> 00:38:21.470
or did you learn slack
key tuning initially?

00:38:21.470 --> 00:38:23.990
&gt;&gt;LEDWARD KAAPANA: I learned
slack key from my dad.

00:38:23.990 --> 00:38:27.860
My dad and my uncles
they awfully standard.

00:38:27.860 --> 00:38:34.790 position:56%
And my dad played guitar, he played
saxophone, piano, violin, auto harp,

00:38:34.790 --> 00:38:38.570
ukulele, you know,
they all played that.

00:38:38.570 --> 00:38:44.460
You know? So, then I played
learning slack key from my dad.

00:38:44.460 --> 00:38:46.530
My mom taught me how to
play standard tuning.

00:38:46.530 --> 00:38:50.740
She told me, you have to learn
how to play the standard tuning.

00:38:50.740 --> 00:38:53.530
I'm glad, and the first
standard tuning was the key of C,

00:38:53.530 --> 00:38:55.930
and I was so small
and I had to stretch.

00:38:55.930 --> 00:38:59.710
And, you know, I said -- oh,
you got to keep on practicing.

00:38:59.710 --> 00:39:04.280
Kept on practicing until
your fingers get used to it.

00:39:04.280 --> 00:39:07.790
And then my uncle told
me you have to use pick.

00:39:07.790 --> 00:39:10.570
Because in Kalapana we
don't have no electricity,

00:39:10.570 --> 00:39:12.390
so nobody can use guitar,

00:39:12.390 --> 00:39:15.510
so I started with holly pick
before I could play without pick.

00:39:15.510 --> 00:39:19.010
So, now I play with pick, so
I cannot play without pick.

00:39:19.010 --> 00:39:21.610
I don't have the pick, I
can't even play the guitar.

00:39:21.610 --> 00:39:23.960
I mean, my fingers
get all tangled up.

00:39:23.960 --> 00:39:28.350
The picks -- one thing with
the pick, the note is clearer.

00:39:28.350 --> 00:39:33.620
I can go loud, I can go
soft, in between, you know.

00:39:33.620 --> 00:39:37.630
There's actually, you know, so, so
that's why when I play with guys

00:39:37.630 --> 00:39:41.860 position:56%
with acoustic they playing without
picks my guitar is louder than them.

00:39:41.860 --> 00:39:47.130
so, when it comes to their turn
to play the lead I just back off

00:39:47.130 --> 00:39:50.720
on my picking, because I go soft,
you know, if I'm picking loudly,

00:39:50.720 --> 00:39:53.510
if I'm picking loud it go --

00:39:53.510 --> 00:39:59.110
[ Music ]

00:39:59.110 --> 00:40:00.910
Then if I bring it down a little.

00:40:00.910 --> 00:40:05.220
[ Music ]

00:40:05.220 --> 00:40:07.420
So, I just kind of
lighten up on the picks.

00:40:07.420 --> 00:40:08.720
&gt;&gt;JOHN FENN: That's
your volume control.

00:40:08.720 --> 00:40:10.020
&gt;&gt;LEDWARD KAAPANA:
Volume control, yeah.

00:40:10.020 --> 00:40:11.320
I think, yeah.

00:40:11.320 --> 00:40:16.130
So they can hear his guitar,
because he doesn't have a pick.

